# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format uses `[INST]`/`[/INST]` turn markers, prepends system
messages to the first user turn (no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapper), and appends `</s>` (eos_token)
after assistant turns. Unlike Ministral 3 — which uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]...[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]`
wrapping and is already handled by `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3` — this format has no
dedicated specialized handler in `common/chat.cpp`.

The task requires adding only new code. The header `src/llama-chat.h` must not change (no new
enum value), and existing handler functions must not be modified. Therefore, the entire
implementation lives in `common/chat.cpp` (new function + one new `if`-block in the dispatcher)
plus a new Jinja template file.

---

## Key Files

| File | Role | Action |
|------|------|--------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Specialized handler functions + dispatcher | Add new handler + new detection condition |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja` | Jinja template for the format | Create new file |
| `tests/test-chat.cpp` | PEG parser tests | Add new `peg_tester` block |

**Files that must NOT be touched:**
- `src/llama-chat.h` — header, no new enum values
- Any existing `common_chat_params_init_*` function

---

## Why the Detection Is Safe

All four existing templates that contain `[INST]` in `models/templates/` also contain
`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`:
